Topic.Title: BARRONS- Intel: Argus Cuts Q3, Year View on Euro Weakness, Ultrabook Slowness

Message.Msg: Some are hoping they will meet the low end and avoid a preannouncement. Not sure if it makes any difference. Intel: Argus Cuts Q3, Year View on Euro Weakness, Ultrabook Slowness By Tiernan Ray Tags PC ultrabook Windows Argus Research’s Jim Kelleher this morning joins the discussion this week on whether Intel (INTC) will meet this quarter’s expectations on the Street. The current consensus is $14.25 billion and 60 cents per share in profit. Kelleher, who has a Buy rating on Intel and a $34 price target, thinks Intel will report just under the midpoint of its forecast range for $13.8 billion to $14.8 billion, or slightly less than $14.2 billion. Kelleher has reduced his estimates after concluding that the company is contending with economic pressures, as well as the slow ramp of “ultrabook” computers it has been endorsing, and the slow development of tablets based on Microsoft‘s (MSFT) Windows: Intel may deliver calendar 3Q12 revenue toward the low end of guidance, in our view, based on Persistent macro-economic headwinds buffeting the global economy and particularly Europe. In addition to weaker revenue, Intel could see a less-favorable CPU mix, based on signs that the Ultrabook – which uses some of Intel’s highest-end PC processors – has not really caught on yet. We expect Intel’s overall volumes to remain reasonably good, based on emerging economy demand; but we expect the Ultrabook ramp to be slower in emerging economies compared with mature nations. Thus, Intel’s emerging economy mix is likely to remain below company margins. In addition to economic headwinds and competitive pressures from tablets, Ultrabook is being impacted by its lack of alignment with the Windows 8 launch, which will not take place until October 2012. Based on past precedent, Windows 8 will likely ramp slowly, with slightly better early uptake by consumers; enterprise buying of PCs with Windows 8 will likely be pushed into 2013.

Message.Title: Bernanke Gives Market QE3 Reasons to Rally
Message.Msg: August 31, 2012, 11:28 AM . Bernanke Gives Market QE3 Reasons to Rally . MarketBeat HOME PAGE By Steven Russolillo FactSet The Dow’s intraday chart (click for bigger image). This is just about everything the bulls could have wanted. After some choppy trading immediately following the release of Bernanke’s speech, stocks are trading around session highs. Investors are finding comfort in the Fed Chairman’s comments that more stimulus could be coming sooner than later. “Bernanke left the door wide open to more QE,” says Alan Ruskin, a strategist at Deutsche Bank DBK.XE +5.06%. “I think the US equity market has either the benefit of stronger US data coming down the pike, or QE3, and is relatively well protected, so this is good for macro risk.” The Dow recently rose 137 points, or 1.1%, to 13138, with Friday’s gains pushing the blue-chip index back into positive territory for the month of August. All 30 Dow components are trading higher, led higher by Intel INTC +2.68%, Hewlett-Packard HPQ +1.55% and Microsoft MSFT +1.68%. But Friday’s action has been choppier than usual, at least compared to the market action throughout the summer. The Dow was up more than 100 points before Bernanke’s speech was released, then pared gains and was up only 20 points minutes after the release and now has reverted back toward the day’s highs. Perhaps no explicit mention of QE3 prompted the initial downdraft. But now, the consensus seems to think Bernanke’s speech did nothing to change the view that more unconventional accommodation is coming soon. The euro is also jumping, pushing back above $1.26, while the dollar continues to fall. “The U.S. dollar will remain marginally vulnerable to an ongoing euro short squeeze,” Ruskin says. Furthermore, Dan Greenhaus, chief global strategist at BTIG, said Bernanke’s speech didn’t dissuade his view that the Fed is likely to extend its rate-guidance adjustments. Greenhaus also thinks there’s a greater than 50% chance of another bond-buying program, or QE3, to be announced at the September meeting. “The speech doesn’t necessarily add anything new to the current debate about what the Fed may or may not do in September,” Greenhaus says. “It colors in slightly the Chairman’s thinking, but after the last FOMC minutes, it would have been hard, short of outright saying ‘QE3 is coming’ for the Chairman to boost expectations much further. In that regard, we are unsurprised.” For more MarketBeat and other streaming markets coverage from The Wall Street Journal.....
